page.title: Formatting
page.text:
Tuple has one element for each \dred{place holder} in the |format_string|. Place holders are:
\begin{itemize} \item |%d| for integers in decimal, \item |%g| for |float|, \item |%.2f| for |float| with fixed precision (2 digits after period), \item |%s| for anything (like |str(x)|). \end{itemize}

page.title: Formatting
Strings
page.text: Strings are \dred{immutable}.

The |in| operator for strings:
\begin{V} >>> "abc" in "01234abcdefg" True >>> "abce" in "01234abcdefg" False \end{V}
Different from the |in| operator for lists and tuples, which tests whether something is equal to an element of the list or tuple.

page.title: String methods
page.text:
String objects have many useful methods:
\begin{itemize} \item |upper()|, |lower()|, and |capitalize()| \item |isalpha()| and |isdigit()| \item |startswith(prefix)| and |endswith(suffix)| \item |find(str)|, |find(str, start)|, and |find(str, start, end)|\\ (return -1 if |str| is not |in| the string) \item |replace(str1, str2)| \item |rstrip()|, |lstrip()| and |strip()| to remove white space on the right, left, or both ends. \end{itemize}

page.title: Case study: Mastermind
page.text: You all know the mastermind game:
We implement a simple text version: colored pegs are the six letters A - F. The secret has four letters, all distinct.

\begin{V} 1: ABCD : 1 positions, 2 letters 2: ABDF : 0 positions, 3 letters 3: CAFB : 1 positions, 1 letters 4: EBAD : 2 positions, 2 letters 5: BEAD : 1 positions, 3 letters Enter your guess> EABD My secret was EABD, you guessed in 6 guesses! \end{V}

page.title: Chromakey
page.text: \dred{Chromakey} is a technique to overlay one scene on top of another one. It is commonly used for weather maps.

page.title: Color distance
page.text: This is just the Euclidean distance in $\mathbb{R}^3$.

page.title: Chromakey
Information hiding
page.text: Humans cannot perceive a small change in light intensity or color value. We can use this to hide information inside images.
To decode the secret, we look at all pixels~|(r,g,b)| of the image, and turn it black if |r| is odd, and white otherwise.
